translation.displayName: Personal history of transient ischemic attack (TIA), and cerebral infarction without residual deficits

tr.td: Title: OV: multiple issues
Author: Akande MD, Olusina

1. Essential hypertension I10
Chronic, controlled.
Complicated by patient's other comorbidities, most likely complicated by the patient's lifestyle along with her history of CVA.
Meds: No current changes in management. The patient will continue to take amlodipine and olmesartan.
Labs: Future labs have been sent.
Imaging: EKG is not on file.
Counseling: Lifestyle changes such as low salt diet, activity, and excess alcohol.
2. History of CVA (cerebrovascular accident) without residual deficits Z86.73
Chronic, stable.
No changes in management. The patient will continue to take pravastatin.
3. CKD stage G3b/A1, GFR 30-44 and albumin creatinine ratio <30 mg/g N18.32
New diagnosis, uncontrolled.
Meds: N/A
Labs: On the review of the patient's labs and history, there does seem to be a slow increase in her creatinine with a decrease in her GFR. A repeat BMP has been sent.
Imaging: N/A
Referral: N/A
Counseling: N/A
4. Depression with anxiety F41.8
Chronic, stable.
The patient will continue to take venlafaxine.
5. Peripheral vascular disease, unspecified I73.9
The patient does have a history of CVA but has never had a diagnosis of peripheral vascular disease.
